Since the contrary salts in the water in which quicklime has been slaked arc but little lit for entering into a very close union and for mutually destroying each others powers, each ol them consequently can perlorm the operations appropriate to its own nature. And this is seen clearly in sal armoniae, in which the' aeid salt is combined with a volatile salt, and yet that acid salt is not so completely subdued by its unequal adversary, the volatile salt united with it, as to be unable to dissolve· iron as acids do and to change it into vitriol. Yet il any fixed salt contends with the acid armoniae salt, then indeed its strength is com- pletely destroyed so that it is quite incapable of dis· solving iron any longer. And the case in lact seems to be similar in water of quicklime, lor here the less opposing salts do not so· completely destroy each other but that either ol them can act according to its nature. For the fixed salt ol that water is able to dissolve sulphur, and its acid salt can fix and destroy volatile salts, as was said above.
